    .custom-guidelines li::before {
        content: "✔";
        color: #27ae60;
        font-weight: bold;
        display: inline-block;
        width: 20px;
    }

    @media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
        .custom-guidelines .container {
            width: 95%;
        }

        .custom-guidelines h1 {
            font-size: 24px;
        }

        .custom-guidelines p, .custom-guidelines h2 {
            font-size: 18px;
        }
    }
</style>

<div class="custom-guidelines">
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Guidelines for a Successful Poster Session</h1>
        <p>A poster session is an excellent opportunity for researchers, students, and professionals to present their work and engage in discussions with their peers. To ensure a successful poster session, follow these guidelines:</p>

        <ul>
            <li><b>Clear and Concise Title:</b> Choose a descriptive and attention-grabbing title for your poster. It should clearly convey the main focus of your research or project.</li>
            <li><b>Organized Layout:</b> Organize your poster in a logical flow from top to bottom and left to right. Use headings, subheadings, and numbered sections to make it easy for viewers to follow your content.</li>
            <li><b>Eye-catching Design:</b> Use visually appealing colors, graphics, and images that complement your content. Ensure that the text is readable from a reasonable distance.</li>
            <li><b>Brief Introduction:</b> Provide a brief introduction that sets the context of your research or project. Clearly state the objectives and the problem you aim to address.</li>
            <li><b>Methods and Materials:</b> Describe the methods and materials used in your study or project. Keep it succinct but provide enough information for viewers to understand your approach.</li>
            <li><b>Results and Findings:</b> Highlight your key findings and results using graphs, charts, tables, or images. Emphasize the most significant outcomes.</li>
            <li><b>Discussion and Interpretation:</b> Offer an interpretation of your results and their implications. Be prepared to engage in a discussion about your findings with visitors.</li>
            <li><b>Conclusion:</b> Summarize your research's main points and the potential impact of your work. Reiterate the key takeaways you want viewers to remember.</li>
            <li><b>Acknowledgments:</b> Acknowledge any individuals or institutions that contributed to your research or project.</li>
            <li><b>Personal Presence:</b> During the poster session, be available at your poster to discuss your work with attendees. Be approachable, enthusiastic, and ready to answer questions.</li>
            <li><b>Practice Your Pitch:</b> Prepare a concise and engaging verbal presentation of your poster. Practice your pitch to effectively communicate your work in a few minutes.</li>
            <li><b>Handouts:</b> Consider providing handouts with additional information or contact details for interested viewers to take away.</li>
            <li><b>Time Management:</b> Manage your time effectively during the session. Give each viewer ample time to engage with you, but also be mindful of others who may want to see your poster.</li>
            <li><b>Be Open to Feedback:</b> Be open to constructive feedback and different perspectives on your research. Consider it as an opportunity for growth and improvement.</li>
            <li><b>Respect Other Presenters:</b> Be respectful of other presenters and their time. Visit other posters and engage in meaningful discussions with fellow participants.</li>
            <li><b>Follow Up:</b> After the session, follow up with individuals who expressed interest in your work. Share additional materials or collaborate further if applicable.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Remember, a poster session is not just about showcasing your work; it's also about networking, learning from others, and building connections in your field. Enjoy the experience and make the most out of the opportunity to share your research with the community.</p>
    </div>
</div>
